aspace_helpers.title: "Princeton University" should be a corporate body Agent in ASpace

comments.body:
Implementation note: The current logic in aspace2alma is: if the double dash is followed by numbers, make it a date subdivision, else make it a topical subdivision.

Checking for form (or, for that matter, geographical) subdivisions would require terms dictionaries to check against, which is both expensive and not terribly robust.

comments.body: @christinach and I looked at this today.  The generated_date of January 1 is expected (this is when PUL requested the dump via the SCSB API).  This does not explain the very old incrementals (e.g. from 2 years ago) that were being indexed before.  However, since those incrementals have been deleted now, we'll close this issue for now, and troubleshoot further if it happens again.

figgy.title: Update universalviewer from 3 to 4, use package via yarn
Language Field in figgy not pulling/viewing correct languages from MARC record

comments.body: I know we made a number of changes in language display functionality in Orangelight/Bibdata, which is probably part of this. See https://github.com/pulibrary/bibdata/issues/2069 which is referenced by a few PRs.
ok, so from what I see, Minjie's thought Re Figgy not being able to interpret the language code when it is taken from iso639 is possible/probable?
Yes, that is my guess — maybe if there are only ISO 639-3 languages, then there's a problem parsing them?

Yes, I too suspect that ISO 639-3 language codes are trigging Figgy up.

Here is the context: [ISO 639-3 language codes](https://iso639-3.sil.org/code_tables/639/data) were applied only recently to a small number of our bibs [like these](https://catalog.princeton.edu/?f1=all_fields&f2=author&f3=title&f_inclusive%5Blanguage_facet%5D%5B%5D=Munsee&f_inclusive%5Blanguage_facet%5D%5B%5D=Wu+Chinese&op2=AND&op3=AND&q1=&q2=&q3=&range%5Bpub_date_start_sort%5D%5Bbegin%5D=&range%5Bpub_date_start_sort%5D%5Bend%5D=&search_field=advanced&sort=pub_date_start_sort+asc%2C+title_sort+asc%2C+score+desc). ISO 639-3 is much larger than "MARC Code List for Languages" so is able to match up with world languages, including indigenous languages and dialects, in greater granularity.
Confirmation from Anu regarding priority: _It’s not time-sensitive – by April [2023] or so, would be ideal._
@dependabot rebase
